rder border-border bg-muted px-1.5 text-[10px] font-mono\">/</kbd></a><a class=\"rounded-md px-2.5 py-1.5 text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground\" href=\"/dashboard\">Progress</a><button class=\"inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 rounded-lg font-medium transition-colors focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 hover:bg-muted text-foreground h-9 w-9\" aria-label=\"Toggle theme\"></button></div></div></header><main id=\"main\" class=\"min-h-[70vh]\"><div class=\"container-af py-8\"><script type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"Article\",\"headline\":\"Apply Operations to Maximize Score\",\"description\":\"Original Hard explanation for Apply Operations to Maximize Score (LeetCode #2818). Pattern: stack. Time O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn), space O(sqrt(r) + n). Multi-language solutions and interview tips.\",\"url\":\"https://algoforge.dev/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score\",\"author\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"AlgoForge\"},\"publisher\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"AlgoForge\"},\"datePublished\":\"2026-01-01\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-07-17\"}</script><script type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"FAQPage\",\"mainEntity\":[{\"@type\":\"Question\",\"name\":\"What is the time complexity of Apply Operations to Maximize Score?\",\"acceptedAnswer\":{\"@type\":\"Answer\",\"text\":\"The reference solutions aim for O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn) time and O(sqrt(r) + n) space. Always re-derive complexity from the code you write in the interview.\"}},{\"@type\":\"Question\",\"name\":\"What pattern does Apply Operations to Maximize Score use?\",\"acceptedAnswer\":{\"@type\":\"Answer\",\"text\":\"It primarily maps to stack, greedy, sort, and heap, within the broader topic of binary heap.\"}},{\"@type\":\"Question\",\"name\":\"Is Apply Operations to Maximize Score good for interviews?\",\"acceptedAnswer\":{\"@type\":\"Answer\",\"text\":\"Yes — as a Hard problem it is a solid practice target. Pair it with related problems in the same pattern family for spaced repetition.\"}},{\"@type\":\"Question\",\"name\":\"Where can I read the official statement?\",\"acceptedAnswer\":{\"@type\":\"Answer\",\"text\":\"Open the official LeetCode page for constraints and examples: https://leetcode.com/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score/\"}}]}</script><script type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"HowTo\",\"name\":\"How to solve Apply Operations to Maximize Score\",\"description\":\"Original Hard explanation for Apply Operations to Maximize Score (LeetCode #2818). Pattern: stack. Time O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn), space O(sqrt(r) + n). Multi-language solutions and interview tips.\",\"step\":[{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":1,\"text\":\"Read the official problem statement on LeetCode\"},{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":2,\"text\":\"Solve on paper / whiteboard first\"},{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":3,\"text\":\"Implement the stack, greedy, sort, and heap approach\"},{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":4,\"text\":\"Verify edge cases from the checklist\"},{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":5,\"text\":\"State time and space complexity aloud\"},{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":6,\"text\":\"Compare with the AlgoForge reference solution\"},{\"@type\":\"HowToStep\",\"position\":7,\"text\":\"Schedule a revision session\"}]}</script><nav aria-label=\"Breadcrumb\" class=\"text-sm text-muted-foreground\"><script type=\"application/ld+json\">{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BreadcrumbList\",\"itemListElement\":[{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":1,\"name\":\"Home\",\"item\":\"https://algoforge.dev/\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":2,\"name\":\"Problems\",\"item\":\"https://algoforge.dev/problems\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":3,\"name\":\"Apply Operations to Maximize Score\",\"item\":\"https://algoforge.dev/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score\"}]}</script><ol class=\"flex flex-wrap items-center gap-1.5\"><li class=\"flex items-center gap-1.5\"><a class=\"hover:text-primary transition-colors\" href=\"/\">Home</a></li><li class=\"flex items-center gap-1.5\"><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"text-border\">/</span><a class=\"hover:text-primary transition-colors\" href=\"/problems\">Problems</a></li><li class=\"flex items-center gap-1.5\"><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"text-border\">/</span><span class=\"text-foreground font-medium\" aria-current=\"page\">Apply Operations to Maximize Score</span></li></ol></nav><div class=\"mt-6 grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_280px] gap-10\"><article><header class=\"space-y-4\"><div class=\"flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2\"><span class=\"text-sm text-muted-foreground tabular-nums\">#<!-- -->2818</span><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide bg-hard/15 text-hard\">Hard</span><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\">~<!-- -->50<!-- --> min</span></div><h1 class=\"text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight\">Apply Operations to Maximize Score</h1><p class=\"text-muted-foreground max-w-2xl\">Time <strong class=\"text-foreground\">O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn)</strong> · <!-- -->Space <strong class=\"text-foreground\">O(sqrt(r) + n)</strong> · <a href=\"https://leetcode.com/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" class=\"text-primary underline-offset-2 hover:underline\">Official statement on LeetCode</a></p><div class=\"flex flex-wrap gap-2\"><a href=\"/topics/binary-heap\"><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide bg-primary/15 text-primary\">binary heap</span></a><a href=\"/patterns/stack\"><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\">stack</span></a><a href=\"/patterns/greedy\"><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\">greedy</span></a><a href=\"/patterns/sort\"><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\">sort</span></a><a href=\"/patterns/heap\"><span class=\"inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide border border-border text-muted-foreground\">heap</span></a></div><div class=\"flex flex-wrap gap-2 pt-1\"><button class=\"inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 rounded-lg font-medium transition-colors focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 border border-border bg-card hover:bg-muted text-foreground h-8 px-3 text-sm\" type=\"button\" aria-pressed=\"false\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-bookmark h-4 w-4\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path d=\"M17 3a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v15a1 1 0 0 1-1.496.868l-4.512-2.578a2 2 0 0 0-1.984 0l-4.512 2.578A1 1 0 0 1 5 20V5a2 2 0 0 1 2-2z\"></path></svg>Bookmark</button><a class=\"text-sm text-primary hover:underline\" href=\"/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score/cpp\">cpp</a><a class=\"text-sm text-primary hover:underline\" href=\"/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score/python\">python</a></div></header><section class=\"mt-10\" id=\"solutions\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\">Solutions</h2><div class=\"rounded-xl border border-border overflow-hidden bg-code-bg text-slate-100\"><div class=\"flex flex-wrap items-center justify-between gap-2 border-b border-white/10 bg-black/30 px-2 py-1.5\"><div class=\"flex flex-wrap gap-1\" role=\"tablist\" aria-label=\"Language\"><button role=\"tab\" aria-selected=\"true\" class=\"rounded-md px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-medium transition-colors bg-white/15 text-white\">C++</button><button role=\"tab\" aria-selected=\"false\" class=\"rounded-md px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-medium transition-colors text-slate-400 hover:text-white hover:bg-white/5\">Python</button></div><button class=\"inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 rounded-lg font-medium transition-colors focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 px-3 text-sm text-slate-300 hover:text-white hover:bg-white/10 h-8\" type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Copy code\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-copy h-3.5 w-3.5\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><rect width=\"14\" height=\"14\" x=\"8\" y=\"8\" rx=\"2\" ry=\"2\"></rect><path d=\"M4 16c-1.1 0-2-.9-2-2V4c0-1.1.9-2 2-2h10c1.1 0 2 .9 2 2\"></path></svg>Copy</button></div><pre class=\"overflow-x-auto p-4 text-[13px] leading-relaxed font-mono max-h-[32rem]\"><code>// Time:  O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + pi(sqrt(r))) + klogn) = O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn), m is max(k for _, k in queries), pi(n) = number of primes in a range [1, n] = O(n/logn) by prime number theorem, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem\n// Space: O(sqrt(r) + n)\n\n// number theory, mono stack, greedy, sort, heap\nclass Solution {\npublic:\n    int maximumScore(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums, int k) {\n        static const int MOD = 1e9 + 7;\n        const auto&amp; addmod = [&amp;](uint32_t a, uint32_t b) {  // avoid overflow\n            a %= MOD, b %= MOD;\n            if (MOD - a &lt;= b) {\n                b -= MOD;  // relied on unsigned integer overflow in order to give the expected results\n            }\n            return a + b;\n        };\n\n        const auto&amp; mulmod = [&amp;](uint32_t a, uint32_t b)  {  // avoid overflow\n            a %= MOD, b %= MOD;\n            uint32_t result = 0;\n            if (a &lt; b) {\n                swap(a, b);\n            }\n            while (b &gt; 0)  { \n                if (b % 2 == 1) {\n                    result = addmod(result, a);\n                }\n                a = addmod(a, a);\n                b /= 2; \n            } \n            return result; \n        };\n\n        const auto&amp; powmod = [&amp;](uint32_t a, uint32_t b) {\n            a %= MOD;\n            uint32_t result = 1;\n            while (b) {\n                if (b &amp; 1) {\n                    result = mulmod(result, a);\n                }\n                a = mulmod(a, a);\n                b &gt;&gt;= 1;\n            }\n            return result;\n        };\n    \n        const auto&amp; linear_sieve_of_eratosthenes = [](int n) {  // Time: O(n), Space: O(n)\n            vector&lt;int&gt; spf(n + 1, -1);\n            vector&lt;int&gt; primes;\n            for (int i = 2; i &lt;= n; ++i) {\n                if (spf[i] == -1) {\n                    spf[i] = i;\n                    primes.emplace_back(i);\n                }\n                for (const auto&amp; p : primes) {\n                    if (i * p &gt; n || p &gt; spf[i]) {\n                        break;\n                    }\n                    spf[i * p] = p;\n                }\n            }\n            return primes;\n        };\n    \n        const auto&amp; primes = linear_sieve_of_eratosthenes(sqrt(*max_element(cbegin(nums), cend(nums))));\n        unordered_map&lt;int, int&gt; lookup;\n        const auto&amp; count_of_distinct_prime_factors = [&amp;](int x) {\n            const int y = x;\n            if (!lookup.count(y)) {\n                int cnt = 0;\n                for (const auto&amp; p : primes) {\n                    if (p * p &gt; x) {\n                        break;\n                    }\n                    if (x % p != 0) {\n                        continue;\n                    }\n                    ++cnt;\n                    for (; x % p == 0; x /= p);\n                }\n                if (x != 1) {\n                    ++cnt;\n                }\n                lookup[y] = cnt;\n            }\n            return lookup[y];\n        };\n\n        vector&lt;int&gt; scores;\n        scores.reserve(size(nums));\n        for (const auto&amp; x : nums) {\n            scores.emplace_back(count_of_distinct_prime_factors(x));\n        }\n\n        vector&lt;int&gt; stk = {-1};\n        vector&lt;int&gt; left(size(scores), -1);\n        for (int i = 0; i &lt; size(scores); ++i) {\n            while (stk.back() != -1 &amp;&amp; scores[stk.back()] &lt; scores[i]) {  // if multiple such elements exist, choose the one with the smallest index\n                stk.pop_back();\n            }\n            left[i] = stk.back();\n            stk.emplace_back(i);\n        }\n        stk = {static_cast&lt;int&gt;(size(scores))};\n        vector&lt;int&gt; right(size(scores), -1);\n        for (int i =  size(scores) - 1; i &gt;= 0; --i) {\n            while (stk.back() != size(scores) &amp;&amp; scores[stk.back()] &lt;= scores[i]) {\n                stk.pop_back();\n            }\n            right[i] = stk.back();\n            stk.emplace_back(i);\n        }\n\n        int result = 1;\n        vector&lt;pair&lt;int, int&gt;&gt; pairs;\n        pairs.reserve(size(nums));\n        for (int i = 0; i &lt; size(nums); ++i) {\n            pairs.emplace_back(nums[i], i);\n        }\n        priority_queue&lt;pair&lt;int, int&gt;&gt; max_heap(cbegin(pairs), cend(pairs));\n        while (!empty(max_heap)) {\n            const auto [_, i] = max_heap.top(); max_heap.pop();\n            const int c = min((i - left[i]) * (right[i] - i), k);\n            result = mulmod(result, powmod(nums[i], c));\n            k -= c;\n            if (!k) {\n                break;\n            }\n        }\n        return result;\n    }\n};\n</code></pre></div></section><section id=\"beginner\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Beginner Explanation</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>What is Apply Operations to Maximize Score?</h2>\n<p><strong>Apply Operations to Maximize Score</strong> (LeetCode #2818) is a <strong>Hard</strong> problem that primarily trains <strong>binary heap</strong>.</p>\n<h3>How to think about it</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Restate the goal</strong> in your own words before coding.</li>\n<li>Work a <strong>tiny example</strong> by hand so the invariant becomes obvious.</li>\n<li>Identify the <strong>pattern</strong> — this problem aligns with <strong>stack, greedy, sort, and heap</strong>.</li>\n<li>Only then translate the idea into code.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Why this problem matters</h3>\n<p>Hard problems force you to combine patterns and prove complexity carefully — interview gold.\nOfficial solution notes mention: Number Theory, Linear Sieve of Eratosthenes, Mono Stack, Greedy.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>AlgoForge explanations are original teaching notes. Always open the <a href=\"https://leetcode.com/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score/\">official problem statement on LeetCode</a> for constraints and examples.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</div></section><section id=\"interview\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Interview Walkthrough</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Interview approach for Apply Operations to Maximize Score</h2>\n<h3>Opening (30–60 seconds)</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Clarify inputs/outputs and edge cases (empty input, single element, duplicates, overflow).</li>\n<li>State a <strong>brute force</strong> so the interviewer knows you can solve it naively.</li>\n<li>Propose the <strong>optimal direction</strong> tied to <strong>stack, greedy, sort, and heap</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Core solution narrative</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Define the <strong>state</strong> you track (pointers, DP cell, set membership, stack top, etc.).</li>\n<li>Explain the <strong>transition</strong> when you process the next element.</li>\n<li>Call out <strong>time</strong> (O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn)) and <strong>space</strong> (O(sqrt(r) + n)) before coding.</li>\n<li>Code cleanly; narrate variable names.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>What interviewers listen for</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Correctness on edge cases</li>\n<li>Complexity honesty</li>\n<li>Ability to discuss <strong>trade-offs</strong> (e.g., hash map space vs. sort + two pointers)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Follow-up questions they may ask</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Can you solve it with less memory?</li>\n<li>What if the input stream is infinite / doesn't fit in RAM?</li>\n<li>How would tests look for adversarial inputs?</li>\n</ul>\n</div></section><section id=\"optimized\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Optimized Approach</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Optimized solution notes</h2>\n<p>The reference solutions on AlgoForge target <strong>O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn)</strong> time and <strong>O(sqrt(r) + n)</strong> space.</p>\n<h3>Pattern focus: stack, greedy, sort, and heap</h3>\n<p>Use the pattern as a checklist:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>stack</strong> — confirm the invariant holds after each step</li>\n<li><strong>greedy</strong> — confirm the invariant holds after each step</li>\n<li><strong>sort</strong> — confirm the invariant holds after each step</li>\n<li><strong>heap</strong> — confirm the invariant holds after each step</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Multiple methods appear in the source solutions — compare them and explain when each is preferable.</p>\n<h3>Implementation tips</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Prefer readable names over micro-optimizations in interviews.</li>\n<li>Extract helpers only when they clarify (e.g., expand-around-center, DFS visit).</li>\n<li>After AC-level logic, re-scan for off-by-one and null checks.</li>\n</ul>\n</div></section><section id=\"complexity\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Complexity Analysis</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Complexity</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Measure</th>\n<th>Bound</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Time</td>\n<td><strong>O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Space</td>\n<td><strong>O(sqrt(r) + n)</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>How to justify this in an interview</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Time:</strong> count loops, map/set operations, and recursive branching; state average vs worst case if relevant.</li>\n<li><strong>Space:</strong> include hash maps, recursion stack, and output allocation when the problem asks for it.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If your implementation differs from the reference, re-derive big-O from <em>your</em> code — never memorize a complexity you cannot defend.</p>\n</div></section><section id=\"common-mistakes\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Common Mistakes</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Common mistakes on Apply Operations to Maximize Score</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Skipping edge cases</strong> — empty collections, single-element inputs, max constraints.</li>\n<li><strong>Wrong invariant</strong> for stack, greedy, sort, and heap — updating state too early or too late.</li>\n<li><strong>Mutating input unexpectedly</strong> when the problem forbids it.</li>\n<li><strong>Off-by-one</strong> in windows, ranges, or binary search bounds.</li>\n<li><strong>Ignoring overflow / precision</strong> for integer arithmetic problems.</li>\n<li><strong>Overengineering</strong> — jumping to an advanced structure when a simpler approach works.</li>\n</ol>\n</div></section><section id=\"alternatives\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Alternative Approaches</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Alternatives</h2>\n<p>The source file includes more than one method. Compare:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Primary optimized path</strong> — best complexity for typical interviews.</li>\n<li><strong>Secondary approach</strong> — often brute force, sorting-based, or space-optimized variant.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Practice articulating <strong>when</strong> you would pick each (constraints, readability, follow-ups).</p>\n</div></section><section id=\"edge-cases\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Edge Cases</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Edge cases checklist</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Minimum input size</li>\n<li>Maximum input size / time limits</li>\n<li>Duplicates and already-sorted input</li>\n<li>Negative numbers / zeros (if applicable)</li>\n<li>Disconnected structures (graphs/trees)</li>\n<li>Single path vs branching recursion depth</li>\n</ul>\n</div></section><section id=\"pattern-recognition\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Pattern Recognition</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Spotting this pattern</h2>\n<p>Signal phrases that point to <strong>stack, greedy, sort, and heap</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sorted input or ability to sort without changing the answer class</li>\n<li>Need for contiguous subarray / substring → consider sliding window</li>\n<li>Need for O(1) membership → hash set/map</li>\n<li>Optimal substructure + overlapping subproblems → DP</li>\n<li>Connectivity / components → graph DFS/BFS or Union-Find</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Primary topics: <strong>binary heap</strong>.</p>\n</div></section><section id=\"follow-ups\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Follow-up Interview Questions</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>Follow-ups</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>How does the solution change if the input is a stream?</li>\n<li>Can you solve it in-place?</li>\n<li>What if duplicates must be handled differently?</li>\n<li>How would you parallelize the approach?</li>\n<li>Design tests that would break a buggy implementation.</li>\n</ol>\n</div></section><section id=\"practice\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><div class=\"flex items-center gap-2 mb-3\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold\">Practice Recommendations</h2></div><div class=\"prose-af\"><h2>What to practice next</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Re-solve <strong>Apply Operations to Maximize Score</strong> in a second language (cpp, python).</li>\n<li>Drill 3–5 more problems tagged <strong>binary heap</strong>.</li>\n<li>Teach the solution out loud in under 5 minutes.</li>\n<li>Add this problem to your revision calendar in 3 days and 14 days.</li>\n</ol>\n</div></section><section id=\"visualization\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\">Visualization</h2><div class=\"rounded-xl border border-dashed border-border bg-muted/40 p-6 text-sm text-muted-foreground\">Conceptual diagram for Apply Operations to Maximize Score: show input structure (binary heap), highlight the moving parts of the stack, greedy, sort, and heap approach, and annotate each step with the maintained invariant and complexity.</div></section><section id=\"checklist\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\">Study checklist</h2><ul class=\"space-y-2\"><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>Read the official problem statement on LeetCode</li><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>Solve on paper / whiteboard first</li><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>Implement the stack, greedy, sort, and heap approach</li><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>Verify edge cases from the checklist</li><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>State time and space complexity aloud</li><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>Compare with the AlgoForge reference solution</li><li class=\"flex gap-2 text-sm\"><span class=\"text-primary\" aria-hidden=\"true\">☐</span>Schedule a revision session</li></ul></section><section id=\"revision\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\">Revision notes</h2><p class=\"text-sm rounded-xl border border-border bg-card p-4\">Apply Operations to Maximize Score (#2818) — Hard. Pattern: stack, greedy, sort, and heap. Complexity: O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn) time / O(sqrt(r) + n) space. Re-derive the invariant before coding.</p></section><section id=\"faq\" class=\"mt-10 scroll-mt-24\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\">FAQs</h2><div class=\"space-y-3\"><details class=\"rounded-xl border border-border bg-card p-4 group\"><summary class=\"font-medium cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between gap-2\">What is the time complexity of Apply Operations to Maximize Score?<span class=\"text-muted-foreground group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform\">+</span></summary><p class=\"mt-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground\">The reference solutions aim for O(sqrt(r) + n * (logr + sqrt(r)/log(sqrt(r))) + klogn) time and O(sqrt(r) + n) space. Always re-derive complexity from the code you write in the interview.</p></details><details class=\"rounded-xl border border-border bg-card p-4 group\"><summary class=\"font-medium cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between gap-2\">What pattern does Apply Operations to Maximize Score use?<span class=\"text-muted-foreground group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform\">+</span></summary><p class=\"mt-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground\">It primarily maps to stack, greedy, sort, and heap, within the broader topic of binary heap.</p></details><details class=\"rounded-xl border border-border bg-card p-4 group\"><summary class=\"font-medium cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between gap-2\">Is Apply Operations to Maximize Score good for interviews?<span class=\"text-muted-foreground group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform\">+</span></summary><p class=\"mt-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground\">Yes — as a Hard problem it is a solid practice target. Pair it with related problems in the same pattern family for spaced repetition.</p></details><details class=\"rounded-xl border border-border bg-card p-4 group\"><summary class=\"font-medium cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between gap-2\">Where can I read the official statement?<span class=\"text-muted-foreground group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform\">+</span></summary><p class=\"mt-3 text-sm text-muted-foreground\">Open the official LeetCode page for constraints and examples: https://leetcode.com/problems/apply-operations-to-maximize-score/</p></details></div></section><section id=\"related\" class=\"mt-12 scroll-mt-24\"><h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-3\">Related problems</h2><div class=\"overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-border\"><table class=\"w-full text-sm\"><thead class=\"bg-muted/60 text-left\"><tr><th class=\"px-3 py-2.5 font-semibold w-16\">#</th><th class=\"px-3 py-2.5 font-semibold\">Title</th><th class=\"px-3 py-2.5 font-semibold hidden sm:table-cell\">Difficulty</th><th class=\"px-3 py-2.5 font-semibold hidden md:table-cell\">Topics</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"border-t border-border hover:bg-muted/40\"><td class=\"px-3 py-2.5 text-muted-foreground tabular-nums\">358</td><td class=\"px-3 py-2.5\"><a class=\"font-medium hover:text-primary\" href=\"/problems/rearrang